When creating a String from an empty char array the constructor for char\* or const char\* is called and during that even though the array is empty and the length is 0 the following code block is called in Resize from the operator = call:

```
    capacity_ = newLength + 1;
    if (capacity_ < MIN_CAPACITY)
        capacity_ = MIN_CAPACITY;
```

With min capacity being 8 they will never evaluate to the same.. Wasn't too sure the route you'd prefer on how to fix this, either not setting if empty or  changing how String::EMPTY works so no fix from my side.

No really a issue though if you use String::Empty() but it has a knock on effect because of comparing a Variant::EMPTY  against a String in the latter format.

Any chance of getting an official Lua binding to Octree:Raycast()? With the PODVector<> binding code in Vector.pkg, it should now be possible. I have successfully implemented a version of it in my own build.

In Container/Vector.pkg:

TOLUA_TEMPLATE_BIND(T, Vector3,RayQueryResult)

(This does require implementation of a != operator for RayQueryResult, at least on MinGW)

In Graphics/Octree.pkg:

// void Raycast(RayOctreeQuery& query) const;
    tolua_outside void OctreeRaycast @ Raycast(PODVector<RayQueryResult> &result, const Ray& ray, RayQueryLevel level, float maxDistance, unsigned char drawableFlags) const;

.
.
.

static void OctreeRaycast(const Octree\* octree, PODVector<RayQueryResult> &result, const Ray& ray, RayQueryLevel level, float maxDistance, unsigned char drawableFlags)
{
    RayOctreeQuery query(result,ray,level,maxDistance,drawableFlags);
    octree->Raycast(query);
}

In Lua code, you can then do a full raycast as:

local resultvec=PODVector_RayQueryResult_()
octree:Raycast(resultvec,ray,RAY_TRIANGLE, maxDistance, DRAWABLE_GEOMETRY)

then iterate the resultvec to get the drawables. If the PODVector_RayQueryResult_ syntax seems clunky, in Vector.pkg you can rename it:

$renaming PODVector<RayQueryResult> @ RayQueryResultVector

to make it more convenient.
